04361nam a22005895i 9780300171846DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20092011ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001718467 a10.12987/97803001718462doi  a(DE-B1597)486659  a(OCoLC)1024028683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aS441b.A482 2011 7aNAT0240002bisacsh04a630.97322200aAmerican Georgics :bWritings on Farming, Culture, and the Land /ced. by Brian Donahue, Sara M. Gregg, Edwin C. Hagenstein. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2009] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aYale Agrarian Studies Series00tFrontmatter -- tBrief Contents -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- t1. Shaping the Agrarian Republic, 1780–1825 -- t2. A Nation of Farmers: The Promise and Peril of American Agriculture, 1825–1860 -- t3. The Machine in the Garden: The Rise of American Romanticism -- t4. Agriculture in an Industrializing Nation, 1860–1910 -- t5. Agrarians in an Industrial Nation, 1900–1945 -- t6. Southern Agrarianism, 1925–1940 -- t7. Back to the Land Again, 1940–Present -- tConclusion: American Agrarianism in the Twenty-first Century -- tBibliography -- tSelection Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Thomas Jefferson's Monticello to Michelle Obama's White House organic garden, the image of America as a nation of farmers has persisted from the beginnings of the American experiment. In this rich and evocative collection of agrarian writing from the past two centuries, writers from Hector St. Jean de Crevecoeur to Wendell Berry reveal not only the great reach and durability of the American agrarian ideal, but also the ways in which society has contested and confronted its relationship to agriculture over the course of generations.Drawing inspiration from Virgil's agrarian epic poem, Georgics, this collection presents a complex historical portrait of the American character through its relationship to the land. From the first European settlers eager to cultivate new soil, to the Transcendentalist, utopian, and religious thinkers of the nineteenth century, American society has drawn upon the vision of a pure rural life for inspiration. Back-to-the-land movements have surged and retreated in the past centuries yet provided the agrarian roots for the environmental movement of the past forty years. Interpretative essays and a sprinkling of illustrations accompany excerpts from each of these periods of American agrarian thought, providing a framework for understanding the sweeping changes that have confronted the nation's landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgricultural ecologyzUnited States. 0aAgriculturezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aNATURE / Essays.2bisacsh1 aDonahue, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGregg, Sara M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHagenstein, Edwin C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030013709540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030017184640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300171846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300171846/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY